# Git Commands Practice


git init
git status
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"
git branch feature-login
git checkout feature-login
git merge feature-login
git push origin main
git pull origin main


1.git init  
Initializes a new Git repository in your project folder.  
Used when starting version control for a new project.

2.git status  
Shows the current state of files in your repository.  
Displays modified, staged, and untracked files.

3.git add .  
Stages all changed files for the next commit.  
Used before committing changes to Git history.

4.git commit -m "message"  
Creates a saved snapshot of your staged changes.  
The message describes what changes were made.

5.git push origin main  
Uploads your local commits to the remote GitHub repository.  
Keeps your online repository updated.

6.git pull origin main  
Downloads the latest changes from the remote repository.  
Useful before starting work to stay updated.


7.git clone repository-link  
Creates a copy of an existing repository on your computer.  
Used when working on a project from GitHub.

8.git log  
Shows the commit history of the repository.  
Displays commit messages, IDs, and timestamps.

9.git rm file-name  
Removes a file from both the project and Git tracking.  
Used when deleting unwanted files.

10.git mv old-name new-name  
Renames or moves a file within the repository.  
Git tracks the change automatically.




















